This paper is primarily focused on designing better neural network architectures for visual recognition, which falls under the category of computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also proposes a new methodology for comparing network architectures, which involves statistical techniques and controlling for confounding factors, which are common themes in machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and neural networks (cs.NE). Additionally, the paper discusses the design spaces used in neural architecture search (NAS), which is a subfield of machine learning and artificial intelligence. Finally, the paper touches on the topic of natural language processing (NLP) by briefly mentioning the use of word embeddings in the NAS design space. However, since NLP is not the primary focus of the paper, it is less likely to be the sub-category.
